Five Things You Need to Know

* From Rachel=E2=80=A6 The latest on Cassandra Grey=E2=80=99s quest to win =
back Violet Grey: It=E2=80=99s been more than seven months since Coupang co=
mpleted its acquisition of Farfetch and all its properties, including Viole=
t Grey=E2=80=93=E2=80=93which I=E2=80=99m hearing may soon be back in the h=
ands of its founder, Cassandra Grey. (Despite Farfetch=E2=80=99s ambitious =
beauty rollout, it was clear that the category was never going to work.) Of=
 course, the real reason Farfetch founder Jos=C3=A9 Neves paid $55 million =
for Violet Grey back in 2021 was because of Grey, herself. In addition to h=
aving a very unique internet presence, she is very well-connected and has a=
 knack for creating elevated brands.

After the
sale, Grey took on a few different jobs at Farfetch, including heading up t=
he incubation arm and advising on the marketplace=E2=80=99s strategy. Farfe=
tch shuttered its beauty business about a year ago, but the fate of Violet =
Grey remained nebulous. In February, I reported that Coupang was planning t=
o offload Violet Grey=E2=80=94and ideally to Grey, who I also heard was int=
erested in buying it back. Now, I=E2=80=99m told that a =E2=80=9Cnew P.E. f=
irm=E2=80=9D has partnered with Grey to buy back the retailer. =E2=80=9CVio=
let Grey has been sold,=E2=80=9D said a source with knowledge of the deal. =
=E2=80=9CThis is part of the refocusing on the core Farfetch marketplace bu=
siness by Coupang.=E2=80=9D The asking price was =E2=80=9Csuper-duper cheap=
,=E2=80=9D but this would surely put some much-needed cash on Violet Grey=
=E2=80=99s balance sheet.

I, for one, am excited to see what happens with the site and the shop on Me=
lrose with Grey and her deputy, Sarah Brown, back in control. Stay tuned fo=
r more updates. (Coupang declined to comment; Grey did not respond to reque=
sts for comment.) =E2=80=94Rachel
* What if=E2=80=A6: Glenn Martens is going to Margiela, Martina Tiefenthale=
r is taking over Jil Sander, and John Galliano=E2=80=A6 is going back to Di=
or to do couture alone? That=E2=80=99s the current speculation among those =
in Paris and Milan, and I reckon one or two of these things may end up bein=
g true.

Regarding the Galliano to couture-only chatter: As I=E2=80=99ve said many t=
imes before, Dior, Chanel, Herm=C3=A8s, and Louis Vuitton are large and com=
plex organizations (and, in the case of Dior and Herm=C3=A8s, publicly trad=
ed entities) that require divisional creative executive oversight. I know f=
or a fact that Dior has considered breaking out the
couture job. (The same conversation happened at Givenchy, actually.) Howeve=
r, I=E2=80=99m less convinced of Tiefenthaler doing Jil Sander, but that is=
 not informed by anything other than the fact that OTB C.E.O. Renzo Rosso i=
s very pro Luke and Lucie Meier.
* Tapestry=E2=80=99s antitrust dance: The fashion group=E2=80=99s court bat=
tle with the F.T.C. started Monday, just as a report surfaced ( https://foo=
twearnews.com/business/mergers-acquisitions/tapestry-selling-stuart-weitzma=
n-sources-1203684220/?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F11%2F2=
