email_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that =
they might sell their shoe brand, Stuart Weitzman. Of course, a move like t=
hat won=E2=80=99t solve their problem with the F.T.C., which is arguing tha=
t Tapestry=E2=80=99s merger with Capri will
create a handbag monopoly, but it makes strategic sense nevertheless. I did=
 a story a long time ago on Stuart Weitzman, the namesake, before he sold t=
o the group. He told me his kids weren=E2=80=99t interested in running the =
business, and he wanted it to go to someone real so that it would be manage=
d with compassion. I suspect that the company will be sold to private equit=
y or one of those brand management firms. The proposition of Stuart Weitzma=
n=E2=80=94well-made, comfortable shoes that aren=E2=80=99t terribly expensi=
ve=E2=80=94remains compelling, but there are simply so many brands of a sim=
ilar size and similar offering.
