Some Notes on the Clothes=E2=80=A6

I haven=E2=80=99t gone to as many shows this season as I usually do. Still,=
 it=E2=80=99s important to me to see as much as I can since what=E2=80=99s =
happening on the runways reflects what=E2=80=99s happening in the business =
and often, if we=E2=80=99re lucky, in the culture.

Overall, I=E2=80=99d say this week demonstrated why New York Fashion Week, =
which is increasingly nebulous, needs to exist=E2=80=94it still brings the =
industry together. More international press members were present (thanks to=
 Ala=C3=AFa, mostly, but also Tory Burch and Michael Kors), and more intern=
ational brands, too, like Off-White=E2=84=A2, Nanushka, Toteme, and Ronald =
van der Kemp. After the Proenza Schouler show last Wednesday (a lifetime ag=
o), I had a conversation with an executive about Jack McCollough and Lazaro=
 Hernandez bringing back The Dress. I thought their take on flounce was fet=
ching and
that the collection was a good overall representation of who they are as de=
signers. They=E2=80=99ve really settled into this position of authority wit=
h no-nonsense women who enjoy fashion, want to look good at work, but are w=
ary of Big European Luxury, which increasingly feels like a scam. I told th=
e executive that I keep buying dresses, even though I don=E2=80=99t have ma=
ny places to wear them. She posited that, post-Covid, fashion has become pa=
rt of the experience. It=E2=80=99s not the thing, but it remains an importa=
nt part of the thing, or something like that.

I could tell you that the Tommy Hilfiger show was an incremental improvemen=
t from last season, design-wise (less costume preppy, more fashion preppy),=
 but the point of that show was the experience, itself: They rented Pete Da=
vidson and Colin Jost=E2=80=99s Staten Island Ferry, and Wu-Tang performed.=
 There were so many performances across the week. St. Vincent got up on a l=
ittle riser for
an acoustic set at Thom Browne=E2=80=99s dinner at the Commerce Inn on Mond=
ay night, co-hosted by Oh, Mary! writer and star Cole Escola. It was mostly=
 famous people (Issa Rae, Justin Theroux) and New York theater people (Patt=
i LuPone, Christine Baranski), who are famous in a different way, and every=
one except for Tracee Ellis Ross and me were wearing Thom Browne. Browne di=
d a big show during June couture, so the guests were sort of the show.

The same went for Eckhaus Latta=E2=80=99s 10-year anniversary dinner, where=
 everyone was asked to wear the brand=E2=80=94preferably, pieces from their=
 own closet. I don=E2=80=99t do that sort of stuff (I=E2=80=99m a journalis=
t!), but in this case I made an exception with a pair of jeans that I bough=
t years ago and wear often. (They make great jeans.) Dinner guests with mor=
e chutzpah than me walked the runway between two long tables in a Tribeca a=
partment while the rest of us slurped Momofuku noodles.
Real people look good in Eckhaus Latta.

Khaite designer Catherine Holstein said backstage that she lightened up thi=
s season=E2=80=94the clothes were airier, easier: I loved the pom-pom macra=
m=C3=A9 and the pinstriped bubble skirt. (A client texted me immediately to=
 say that she was so much happier with this season=E2=80=99s proposition th=
an last.) But she also seemed to lighten up about the whole concept of what=
 a fashion show should be. (For one, the room was white instead of black, a=
nd the lights were bright instead of nonexistent, so we could see where we =
were walking as we took our seats.) Sometimes, sincerity can come off as sa=
nctimony, and the worst thing in the world is a designer who is self-seriou=
s. Holstein figured out this season that you can be a serious person withou=
t taking it all too seriously. I am sure LVMH has tried to hire her for thi=
ngs, and I think she should keep saying no. (But they should also keep tryi=
ng, too.)

You know who is in on the
joke? Monse=E2=80=99s Laura Kim and Fernando Garcia. This season=E2=80=99s =
show=E2=80=94including Tiffany Haddish=E2=80=99s hilarious finale crash=E2=
=80=94was far better than the last. I=E2=80=99m sure they=E2=80=99re riding=
 high on the Michelle Obama moment from the Democratic National Convention,=
 and their confidence showed in the collection, which took full advantage o=
f the Miu Miu vibe washing over this season (shades of blue, schoolgirl str=
ipes) and renewed them with their own tailoring signatures.

But if you=E2=80=99re looking for big ideas in New York, Willy Chavarria wo=
uld like to share a few regarding good trousers and the working class. The =
uniforms of the blue collar are fashion, after all. I watched the show, whi=
ch took all the near-invisible workwear tropes you could name and sharpened=
 them into something impossible to ignore, straight on from the end of the =
runway (they went early, and I was late). The directness of the references =
felt quite political,
actually, and not just the designer=E2=80=99s own ACLU merch. The person wh=
o made me late for the show (just kidding, we were both complicit) said tha=
t he likes Willy because he=E2=80=99s an original.

As for the mainstays=E2=80=94the one-namers=E2=80=94Carolina, Coach, and Ko=
rs all stuck with the plan. Carolina designer Wes Gordon, who hosted a cock=
tail party at his home for his bosses at Puig on Sunday night, understands =
his mandate to make big, beautiful gowns and slim dresses in saturated, fan=
tastical colors. At Coach, I=E2=80=99ve realized that Stuart Vevers is livi=
ng in his own movie, not unlike Ralph Lauren. It=E2=80=99s just that Vevers=
=E2=80=99 world looks less like The Great Gatsby and more like Stranger Thi=
ngs. Michael Kors, king of wings, water, and wheels, turned out his standar=
d lady fair. Difficult to be irked by such conventionally pretty, nice thin=
gs=E2=80=94I love a Michael Kors-designed A-line skirt=E2=80=94but it=E2=80=
=99s undeniable that the brand is in a bit of a stasis
because of the situation with Tapestry, Capri, and the F.T.C., not unlike t=
he rock sculptures that anchored the runway.

Tory Burch=E2=80=99s script is nowhere near finished. For her show in Willi=
amsburg=E2=80=99s old Domino Sugar factory, she covered the space in tiny s=
eafoam green tiles, like the bottom of an old-fashioned pool. You could alm=
ost smell the chlorine. I loved the collection=E2=80=99s ultra-structured s=
houlders, and the woven print that looked like flames but were actually swi=
mmers. And of course, the sparkly swimsuits. Backstage, Tory chatted with h=
er mom, Riva, namesake of the famous, recently relaunched ballet flat, in b=
etween interviews. A reminder that these larger-than-life people are=E2=80=
=A6 still people.

