RIBERS+%288%2F29%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io=
&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

In the midst of New York Fashion Week, Lauren Sherman and I sat down to dis=
cuss one of our favorite shared topics (after Est=C3=A9e Lauder and Glossie=
r, for me, of course) in the industry: LVMH. Obviously, the House of Arnaul=
t is the largest luxury conglomerate in the world, parentco of many of the =
biggest names in fashion, wine, and spirits, among other sectors. In some w=
ays, however, LVMH=E2=80=99s power in beauty is even greater.

The company owns Dior and Sephora=E2=80=94one of the biggest beauty labels =
and the most important retailer in the space, respectively. Its beauty incu=
bator, Kendo, is also responsible for Rihanna=E2=80=99s Fenty Beauty, LVMH=
=E2=80=99s last breakout brand. More recently, another LVMH line, Givenchy =
Beauty, dominated BeautyTok following backlash over the relaunch of its sta=
r product (reformulation is
tricky business, indeed). We get into it all here, in addition to =E2=80=9C=
clean beauty=E2=80=9D and what LVMH should be buying.

$(ad2_title) ( https://oscardelarenta.aiproxies.com/?rdr=3Dhttps://www.osca=
rdelarenta.com/?_aiid=3D15543&utm_source=3Demail&utm_medium=3Dnewsletter&ut=
m_campaign=3Dline-sheet-9-11&cieng=3Decomm-static )

The Clean Fad

Lauren Sherman: One of our shared interests is LVMH. You=E2=80=99ve been so=
 busy with Est=C3=A9e Lauder that you haven=E2=80=99t had time to delve dee=
p into what=E2=80=99s happening at the LVMH beauty division, but I know you=
 have many thoughts. A few weeks ago, you reported on the aftermath of Give=
nchy changing the formula ( https://puck.news/givenchy-prisme-libre-reformu=
lation-disaster-explained/?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F1=
1%2F24%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F29%2F24%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) =
of its setting powder, when all hell broke loose. My takeaway was that they=
 didn=E2=80=99t communicate properly.

Rachel Strugatz: Exactly. Brands like to say that they=E2=80=99re being tra=
nsparent, and then share an ingredient list or other things
that don=E2=80=99t actually matter, but they=E2=80=99re usually not transpa=
rent where it counts. That=E2=80=99s what happened here. It was never going=
 to be sexy, but there was a way for Givenchy and LVMH to explain why they =
switched out this specific ingredient without scaring people or using the c=
lean beauty rhetoric that has started to fall out of favor. That communicat=
ion problem is a pervasive challenge for companies across Big Beauty.

Lauren: So what has happened in the past five years with respect to =E2=80=
=9Cclean beauty=E2=80=9D? How has that discourse changed?

Rachel: It=E2=80=99s the same as any other fad, just like when food brands =
felt they had to ensure that their products were sugar-free or fat-free. Th=
ose trends fell out of favor, largely because consumers eventually got more=
 sophisticated and realized that sugar substitutes weren=E2=80=99t all that=
 healthy, either. Clean beauty is similar, and the trend has also been norm=
alized by the industry to the point
where it isn=E2=80=99t much of a differentiator. I=E2=80=99ve heard that Se=
phora is quietly moving away from Clean at Sephora, which is a big deal.

Lauren: Let=E2=80=99s talk more about Sephora. LVMH acquired it in 1998 for=
 $262 million. It did something like $18 billion in sales in 2023. How has =
Sephora changed the trajectory of the beauty industry?

Rachel: Before Sephora, the only place to buy prestige or high-end beauty p=
roducts was in department stores. So it literally stole the show from them.=
 Now, Sephora is the kingmaker.

Lauren: Obviously, it changed the distribution strategy for so many of thes=
e brands. But unlike fashion, beauty still needs wholesale to scale. How re=
liant are prestige brands on Sephora?

Rachel: You almost always need Sephora or Ulta. If you look at the biggest =
brands, they=E2=80=99re almost always sold at both stores=E2=80=93=E2=80=93=
even Fenty, which is owned by LVMH, is carried at Ulta now. A
lot of Est=C3=A9e Lauder=E2=80=99s troubles in North America have to do wit=
h the fact that they were so late to Sephora and Ulta. Sephora has made mul=
ti-hundred-million or billion-dollar brands out of companies like Drunk Ele=
phant, Charlotte Tilbury, Briogeo, etcetera.

Lauren: In many ways, because of Sephora, LVMH controls the beauty industry=
 even more than fashion. Right now, though, when you look at their brands, =
they=E2=80=99re not that exciting. Fenty Beauty was the last big breakout b=
rand, and they did that through their beauty incubator, Kendo. Does Kendo e=
ven exist anymore?

Rachel: Kendo still exists, but it=E2=80=99s true that Fenty has been its o=
nly star=E2=80=94were it not for Fenty=E2=80=99s success, Kendo would be ir=
relevant and might not even exist. Kat Von D was a huge mess, and Marc Jaco=
bs ceased operations a few years ago, though it=E2=80=99s exciting that it=
=E2=80=99s coming back under new ownership with Coty. I=E2=80=99m told that=
 LVMH knows that they need to go
down-market with Kat Von D, which was probably the first modern influencer-=
celebrity makeup brand. They=E2=80=99ve rebranded it, changed the name, and=
 done everything to try and make it work=E2=80=93=E2=80=93which makes sense=
, because it was such a massive success when it first came out=E2=80=93=E2=
=80=93but LVMH doesn=E2=80=99t really do down-market.

Structural Questions

Lauren: On the fashion side, LVMH doesn=E2=80=99t share information between=
 brands in order to encourage competition. On the beauty side, I=E2=80=99m =
sure they share factories and things like that, but it doesn=E2=80=99t soun=
d like they=E2=80=99re really talking to each other that much.

Rachel: LVMH=E2=80=99s beauty portfolio is both very siloed and very divers=
e. Dior is such a powerhouse, and Sephora is the most influential beauty re=
tailer in the world. But then they have these brands that they don=E2=80=99=
t really do anything with anymore, like Fresh. Does anyone remember Fresh? =
That was a good brand that had hero products, and things it was actually kn=
own for.

Lauren: Yes, and there=E2=80=99s Benefit, too. The one thing about Benefit =
that stands out to me is that it was an early D.T.C. beauty brand, and they=
 have all these stores and
products that I=E2=80=99ve been using for 20 years. But it doesn=E2=80=99t =
feel like there is a lot of innovation.

Rachel: In August, Benefit was Sephora=E2=80=99s 11th-best-selling brand. S=
o it=E2=80=99s still a top brand. But you=E2=80=99re right: While it was ve=
ry early to embrace blogger and influencer culture, and it did a great job =
of expanding its brow and blush categories, in the last few years, it feels=
 more like a Steady Eddie or Clinique. It=E2=80=99s a brand that seems unde=
rnourished=E2=80=94it would be in the zeitgeist if LVMH paid more attention=
 to it.

Lauren: You write a lot about M&A, and the conversations that go on forever=
 and never go anywhere. But everyone=E2=80=99s always having conversations,=
 and everything is always for sale. What do you think LVMH should buy?

Rachel: Westman Atelier would be a phenomenal addition to their portfolio: =
It feels like real, luxury makeup in a way most brands could never execute =
without the heritage of an Herm=C3=A8s
or Dior. Likewise, acquiring Makeup by Mario, which is the hot brand everyo=
ne expects to set the market, would also give them a strong, prestige =E2=
=80=9Cartistry=E2=80=9D makeup brand. I don=E2=80=99t think that LVMH is go=
ing to buy it=E2=80=94I=E2=80=99m betting on someone else=E2=80=94but I wou=
ld be pleasantly surprised if they did.

And finally=E2=80=A6 I=E2=80=99m not a dupes person, but I saw an editor-in=
-chief wearing this chunky knit from COS ( https://www.cos.com/en_usd/women=
