          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">I haven=E2=80=99t g=
one to as many shows this season as I usually do. Still, it=E2=80=99s impor=
tant to me to see as much as I can since what=E2=80=99s happening on the ru=
nways reflects what=E2=80=99s happening in the business and often, if we=E2=
=80=99re lucky, in the culture. <br/><br/>Overall, I=E2=80=99d say this wee=
k demonstrated why New York Fashion Week, which is increasingly nebulous, n=
eeds to exist=E2=80=94it still brings the industry together. More internati=
onal press members were present (thanks to Ala=C3=AFa, mostly, but also Tor=
y Burch and Michael Kors), and more international brands, too, like Off-Whi=
te=E2=84=A2, Nanushka, Toteme, and Ronald van der Kemp. After the Proenza S=
chouler show last Wednesday (a lifetime ago), I had a conversation with an =
executive about <b>Jack McCollough</b> and <b>Lazaro Hernandez </b>bringing=
 back The Dress. I thought their take on flounce was fetching and
that the collection was a good overall representation of who they are as de=
signers. They=E2=80=99ve really settled into this position of authority wit=
h no-nonsense women who enjoy fashion, want to look good at work, but are w=
ary of Big European Luxury, which increasingly feels like a scam. I told th=
e executive that I keep buying dresses, even though I don=E2=80=99t have ma=
ny places to wear them. She posited that, post-Covid, fashion has become pa=
rt of the <i>experience</i>. It=E2=80=99s not the thing, but it remains an =
important part of the thing, or something like that. <br/><br/>I could tell=
 you that the Tommy Hilfiger show was an incremental improvement from last =
season, design-wise (less costume preppy, more fashion preppy), but the poi=
nt of that show was the <i>experience</i>, itself: They rented <b>Pete Davi=
dson</b> and <b>Colin Jost</b>=E2=80=99s Staten Island Ferry, and Wu-Tang p=
erformed. There were <i>so</i> many performances across the week. <b>St. Vi=
ncent </b>got up on a little riser for
an acoustic set at <b>Thom Browne</b>=E2=80=99s dinner at the Commerce Inn =
on Monday night, co-hosted by <i>Oh, Mary!</i> writer and star <b>Cole Esco=
la</b>. It was mostly famous people (<b>Issa Rae</b>, <b>Justin Theroux</b>=
) and New York theater people (<b>Patti LuPone</b>, <b>Christine Baranski</=
b>), who are famous in a different way, and everyone except for <b>Tracee E=
llis Ross</b> and me were wearing Thom Browne. Browne did a big show during=
 June couture, so the guests were sort of the show. <br/><br/>The same went=
 for Eckhaus Latta=E2=80=99s 10-year anniversary dinner, where everyone was=
 asked to wear the brand=E2=80=94preferably, pieces from their own closet. =
I don=E2=80=99t do that sort of stuff (I=E2=80=99m a journalist!), but in t=
his case I made an exception with a pair of jeans that I bought years ago a=
nd wear often. (They make great jeans.) Dinner guests with more chutzpah th=
an me walked the runway between two long tables in a Tribeca apartment whil=
e the rest of us slurped Momofuku noodles.
Real people look good in Eckhaus Latta. <br/><br/>Khaite designer <b>Cather=
ine Holstein</b> said backstage that she lightened up this season=E2=80=94t=
he clothes were airier, easier: I loved the pom-pom macram=C3=A9 and the pi=
nstriped bubble skirt. (A client texted me immediately to say that she was =
so much happier with this season=E2=80=99s proposition than last.) But she =
also seemed to lighten up about the whole concept of what a fashion show sh=
ould be. (For one, the room was white instead of black, and the lights were=
 bright instead of nonexistent, so we could see where we were walking as we=
 took our seats.) Sometimes, sincerity can come off as sanctimony, and the =
worst thing in the world is a designer who is self-serious. Holstein figure=
d out this season that you can be a serious person without taking it all to=
o seriously. I am sure LVMH has tried to hire her for things, and I think s=
he should keep saying no. (But they should also keep trying, too.) <br/><br=
/>You know who is in on the
joke? Monse=E2=80=99s <b>Laura Kim</b> and <b>Fernando Garcia</b>. This sea=
son=E2=80=99s show=E2=80=94including <b>Tiffany Haddish</b>=E2=80=99s hilar=
ious finale crash=E2=80=94was far better than the last. I=E2=80=99m sure th=
ey=E2=80=99re riding high on the <b>Michelle Obama </b>moment from the Demo=
cratic National Convention, and their confidence showed in the collection, =
which took full advantage of the Miu Miu vibe washing over this season (sha=
des of blue, schoolgirl stripes) and renewed them with their own tailoring =
signatures. <br/><br/>But if you=E2=80=99re looking for big ideas in New Yo=
rk, <b>Willy Chavarria</b> would like to share a few regarding good trouser=
s and the working class. The uniforms of the blue collar <i>are</i> fashion=
, after all. I watched the show, which took all the near-invisible workwear=
 tropes you could name and sharpened them into something impossible to igno=
re, straight on from the end of the runway (they went early, and I was late=
). The directness of the references felt quite political,
actually, and not just the designer=E2=80=99s own ACLU merch. The person wh=
o made me late for the show (just kidding, we were both complicit) said tha=
t he likes Willy because he=E2=80=99s an original. <br/><br/>As for the mai=
nstays=E2=80=94the one-namers=E2=80=94Carolina, Coach, and Kors all stuck w=
ith the plan. Carolina designer <b>Wes Gordon</b>, who hosted a cocktail pa=
rty at his home for his bosses at Puig on Sunday night, understands his man=
date to make big, beautiful gowns and slim dresses in saturated, fantastica=
l colors. At Coach, I=E2=80=99ve realized that <b>Stuart Vevers</b> is livi=
ng in his own movie, not unlike Ralph Lauren. It=E2=80=99s just that Vevers=
=E2=80=99 world looks less like <i>The Great Gatsby</i> and more like <i>St=
ranger Things</i>. Michael Kors, king of wings, water, and wheels, turned o=
ut his standard lady fair. Difficult to be irked by such conventionally pre=
tty, nice things=E2=80=94I love a Michael Kors-designed A-line skirt=E2=80=
=94but it=E2=80=99s undeniable that the brand is in a bit of a stasis
because of the situation with Tapestry, Capri, and the F.T.C., not unlike t=
he rock sculptures that anchored the runway.<br/><br/><b>Tory Burch</b>=E2=
=80=99s script is nowhere near finished. For her show in Williamsburg=E2=80=
=99s old Domino Sugar factory, she covered the space in tiny seafoam green =
tiles, like the bottom of an old-fashioned pool. You could almost smell the=
 chlorine. I loved the collection=E2=80=99s ultra-structured shoulders, and=
 the woven print that looked like flames but were actually swimmers. And of=
 course, the sparkly swimsuits. Backstage, Tory chatted with her mom, <b>Ri=
va</b>, namesake of the famous, recently relaunched ballet flat, in between=
 interviews. A reminder that these larger-than-life people are=E2=80=A6 sti=
ll people.<br/></td>
         </tr>
